Load NYC Airbnb data, clean/mutate/filter

data("nyc_airbnb")

nyc_airbnb = 
  nyc_airbnb %>% 
  mutate(stars = review_scores_location / 2) %>% 
  rename(
    borough = neighbourhood_group,
    neighborhood = neighbourhood) %>% 
  filter(borough != "Staten Island") %>% 
  select(price, stars, borough, neighborhood, room_type)

Visualizations…

nyc_airbnb %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = stars, y = price)) +
  geom_point()

lots of coefficients, we could use nested datasets and then map across those datasets to build regression models that we care about:

Nesting

nyc_airbnb %>% 
  relocate(borough) %>% 
  nest(data = price:room_type) %>% 
  mutate(
    lm_fits = map(.x = data, ~lm(price ~ stars + room_type, data = .x))
  )
## # A tibble: 4 × 3
##   borough   data                  lm_fits
##   <chr>     <list>                <list> 
## 1 Bronx     <tibble [649 × 4]>    <lm>   
## 2 Queens    <tibble [3,821 × 4]>  <lm>   
## 3 Brooklyn  <tibble [16,810 × 4]> <lm>   
## 4 Manhattan <tibble [19,212 × 4]> <lm>

We’ve created a little dataset that I’m interested in, easier to work with. The mutate means you’re mapping across the data column some function. We have to say price is a function of stars and room type. The .x is wherever we want the object to go, object being the linear model I think.

The lm results are a bit of a mess so we add another line to tidy:

nyc_airbnb %>% 
  relocate(borough) %>% 
  nest(data = price:room_type) %>% 
  mutate(
    lm_fits = map(.x = data, ~lm(price ~ stars + room_type, data = .x)),
    lm_results = map(lm_fits, broom::tidy)
  ) %>% 
  select(borough, lm_results) %>% 
  unnest(lm_results) %>% 
  filter(term == "stars")
## # A tibble: 4 × 6
##   borough   term  estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>     <chr>    <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 Bronx     stars     4.45      3.35      1.33 1.85e- 1
## 2 Queens    stars     9.65      5.45      1.77 7.65e- 2
## 3 Brooklyn  stars    21.0       2.98      7.05 1.90e-12
## 4 Manhattan stars    27.1       4.59      5.91 3.45e- 9

Now we have a 4x5 dataframe. Then we can just selet borough and lm results since we dont’ care about the data, unnest the results, gives dataframe of what effect of stars is in each region. Can then specify the effect of stars.

Let’s look at neighborhoods in Manhattan…

nyc_airbnb %>% 
  filter(borough == "Manhattan") %>% 
  select(-borough) %>% 
  relocate(neighborhood) %>% 
  nest(data = price:room_type)

So for every neighborhood in Manhattan, we see all the variables for the listings (90 air bnbs in flatiron, etc). Dataframe has a column of dataframes.

Effect of room type on outcome, adjusting for stars

manhattan_lm_results_df = 
nyc_airbnb %>% 
  filter(borough == "Manhattan") %>% 
  select(-borough) %>% 
  relocate(neighborhood) %>% 
  nest(data = price:room_type) %>% 
  mutate(
    lm_fits = map(.x = data, ~lm(price ~ stars + room_type, data = .x)),
    lm_results = map(lm_fits, broom::tidy)
  ) %>% 
  select(neighborhood, lm_results) %>% 
  unnest(lm_results)

neighborhood-specific estimates for the coefficients related to room type:

manhattan_lm_results_df %>% 
  filter(str_detect(term, "room_type")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = neighborhood, y = estimate)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  facet_grid(~term) + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 80, hjust = 1))

Getting estimates of impact of increasing star rating on price, adjusting for room type, making denisty plot:

manhattan_lm_results_df %>% 
  filter(term == "stars") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = estimate)) +
  geom_density()

Seems like across all neighborhoods, increasing stars doesn’t have a big effect– some places it goes up a lot, sometimes it becomes cheaper.
